    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast</b> (261Ac). Stands observed on Mount Diablo.</li>
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast Ranges</b> (M262Ac-d, Ai-k). Stands are common in the Temblor and Caliente Range area, where some stands include a rich herbaceous layer (Buck-Diaz et al. 2011), and occur further north into the Panoche Hills (CNPS Vegetation Program 2015).  Stands expected in the Sierra Madre Mountains.</li>
        
            <li><b>Great Valley</b> (262Ag, Aq, Aw, Az). Stands were sampled in the Ciervo Panoche region.  Stands mapped in the southern, southwestern and southeastern San Joaquin Valley (VegCAMP and GIC 2013).</li>
        
            <li><b>Mojave Desert</b> (322Ag). Stands observed from the Mojave Desert include western Antelope Valley, Los Angeles Co. occurring with <i>Eriogonum fasciculatum</i>.</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada</b> (M261Er-s). Stands occur in the southern Sierra Nevada in the Tehachapi Mountains both west and east of the town of Tehachapi (VegCAMP 2015a).</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada Foothills</b> (M261Fd-e). Stands mapped in the foothills of the Tehachapi Mountains (VegCAMP 2015a). Stands observed in the southern Sierra Nevada Foothills in the area of Wind Wolves Preserve.</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Stands occur commonly in the foothills west, south, and east of the San Joaquin Valley. This seral scrub alliance waxes and wanes with related annual and perennial grassland types and coastal scrub. Extended drought periods partially contribute to this fluctuation, as can fire. Livestock do not prefer to eat the character shrubs of this alliance. </div>
</div>

    

    

